originalText.text:
Had a lovely experience, albeit a little overpriced but really what can you expect? The food is pretty good, but the portions are a bit small and some of it is probably replicable elsewhere. The atmosphere and service itself was really great and we had an overall enjoyable time.

The momo mocktail tasted very strongly of shiso rather than peach, if that’s your thing. We also got some sashimi, chicken karaage, and yasai tempura which were all excellent but not phenomenal. Overall, the high price tag and small portion size probably means we won’t dine here often, but a great place to celebrate something or take someone out on a date!

originalText.text:
Kawabun was such an experience, but I did feel like the food taste didn’t fully deliver to my expectations. The shrimp katsu sando was by far the best thing we had- super flavorful and not too heavy. The sticky potato fries were lacking a bit of flavor. The potato salad was very good- it was a nice twist on a classic potato salad with taro in it. The king crab was a bit too fishy for my liking, but it was a beautiful plate. The wagyu presentation and flavors were good, but it was a bit too raw and not seared enough for my taste, so the fat was a little chewy and not rendered. The chicken wings were delicious and the dessert was a nice treat for anyone celebrating there.

Overall, the ambiance and waitstaff were amazing- so that definitely made the experience excellent. I wish the food met the same tier of excellence, and I’m hoping they get their liquor license soon, because the mocktails were amazing.

originalText.text:
We finally visited Kawabun which was highly recommended by our foodie friend. The bar and table for omakase are located on the 1st floor but they are still waiting for alcohol license.

The sides, miso soup and rice that came with the Sansai Set Lunch Menu were impressively authentic in high quality.

The Chicken Shiokoji with Yuzu was soft and juicy with thin fried flour coating & Yuzu flavor. My roommate had Sake Ikura Don with Negitoro and it's really fresh with proper portion. Gindara Saikyou Yaki was flavorful with delicate texture.

originalText.text:
The dining experience was a roller coaster. My friend and I made a last minute reservation for a Saturday evening for a party of two to celebrate a birthday. I did not have expectations, but only knew that the back story of the brand is 400+ years old from Japan. I was excited.

Upon entrance, I adored the exterior structure as well as the interior design. This built my excitement for the food. Being hungry, we ordered and sampled a variety of their dishes. The liquor license is not acquired so no alcohol was served. I noticed the wait staff obviously varied in levels of training as one with work in the food service industry. I found the character and behavior of some of the wait staff to take away from the experience and ambiance the establishment tries to curate and provide for the diners. There were several items that we initially ordered that never arrived because the waitress forgot to place the order. Some of the wait staff were evidently trained in hospitality at a Japanese establishment while others were lacking.

The price we paid for what we received, we felt would have been wonderful…IF all the dishes were executed well. However, some were executed poorly. The hot pot rice with the sea bream was dry, tasteless, colorless and clearly indicated that the kitchen is still working out its menu. The sliced wagyu on the hot stone smelled wonderful, but poorly executed. The wagyu slices were cold in the middle as we bit into them, they should be left on the hot stone longer before bringing to the table without warning.

Pros: The grilled cod was wonderful. The shrimp in portabella mushroom was wonderful. The saba sushi was wonderful. The vegetables were great. All of the portion sizes are on the smaller side.

originalText.text: Had an amazing dinner here where I got to try several of their a la carte dishes. Highlights for me were the karaage, king crab, and wagyu sando. Nice ambiance and service too. They didn't have their cocktail menu available yet but the mocktails were quite tasty.
